Apr 12 2009 	Exceeded my meager expectations......	We had done a lot of research before choosing the Hotel California. I had heard a lot of horror stories about some of the older hotels being smelly, tiny, loud etc..... I had visions of needing constant air freshener and ear plugs. It really wasn't bad. The rooms were definitely small, but not as bad as expected.  The TV was ENORMOUS, but didn't get reception of any kind. We didn't care because we weren't in San Francisco to watch TV. It's just nice to catch the news as you're winding down.  The bathroom was very small ( to be expected) but it was clean. That's all I ask.  There is no air conditioning so if you're planning a summer trip, this would be a consideration. We were there in December so it wasn't an issue for us. The windows do open, but I wouldn't call the air out there &quot;fresh&quot;.  The noise off the street at night is actually quite loud. We were on the 6th floor and our room faced Geary Street. There was no end of sirens and traffic, but that's to be expected in any city.  You aren't but a few blocks off the &quot;Tenderloin&quot; district in this area and so you do get a lot of homeless people milling about. This was mostly from around noon on into the night. It's a minor annoyance. We never felt threatened in any way.  I will say that the halls did smell a little musty and closed up, but hey, it's an old hotel.  The staff left a bit to be desired. They weren't helpful when asking for directions or information. Other than that, they were friendly enough.....just not helpful. Not that it was a big deal, but we weren't offered our free shot of Tequila either.  So, all in all it was a decent stay. There is so much to see in San Francisco that we spent such a tiny amount of time in our room anyway. We literally spent from midnight until 7am in our room to sleep and shower. By the time we got back to the hotel at night we were so exhausted that the noise didn't bother us at all. I wouldn't hesitate to stay here again. The price was right and the location was good. PS. I don't recommend renting a car. Public transit is everywhere and you walk a ton too. Parking is out of this world........ Unless you really must, don't bring a vehicle into the city or rent one.	
Feb 23 2009 	Charming and tasteful	We booked our stay at this hotel from the Hotels.com website and got a great deal. Considering how expensive the rest of the city is, knowing how little we paid (roughly US$82/night inclusive of taxes) made it that much more enjoyable.Don't expect to see a big Best Western sign when looking for the hotel. We had to circle around a few times after getting confused with the one-way streets and not being able to see it the first time around. At the suggestion of another reviewer, we parked in the neighbouring garage and paid $29 a day, which was $30 less than if we had valet parked with the hotel. It was pretty hassel-free, just expensive.While the hotel is on a main road and close to the sights, it's near the sketchy section of Taylor and doesn't feel totally safe sometimes. The number of homeless people and policemen actually surprised us. It wasn't really an area I'd feel comfortable wandering around in.The hotel is charming and doesn't feel like any generic Best Western hotel. The lobby is tastefully decorated and always felt busy. The rooms are small but had everything we needed. You'd likely go stir-crazy if you had to spend a whole day in there, but it was just right for an evening of TV watching. With the queen size bed, they still managed to squeeze in a desk, sitting chair, ottoman, closet and full bathroom.Our room was located right next to the elevator, and if we were ever to return, we'd request a room further away. The doors aren't very sound proof and the old-school elevator makes a loud dinging sound each time it arrives at the floor. We mostly took the stairs to avoid waiting for it. And like any old building, the floors aren't sound-proof either so we often heard the neighbours above us walking around.Good points: great price, clean, well-decorated, plush towels, in-room safety deposit box, friendly and helpful front desk staff, complimentary coffee in the lobby in the morning and wine and cheese in the afternoons.Not so good points: sketchy area, not very soundproof rooms, small rooms.	
