Apr 15 2008 	Had a great stay at the Hotel California	We loved this hotel for its character and personality, as well as the amenities and the service. The staff was always friendly and helpful. The complimentary wine and cheese receptions were a highlight, with California wine! We also had free round-the-clock coffee and hot tea. There's a great lobby with huge comfortable chairs, and a media room at the mezzanine level with additional seating, a computer, and a printer, where I was able to print our boarding passes. Another guest computer is available at the front desk. The free high-speed wireless was wonderful. (I always resent having to pay $10 a day or so for wireless access at pricier hotels.) From the music in the lobby to the pictures on the walls, the decor set the mood: very vintage San Francisco, with curving, carpeted stairways, high ceilings, and hardwood floors, with a definite European feel. The hotel was built in 1906 but underwent a major refurb a year ago. Our yellow room with blue and white bedding was not large, but adequate. The safe in the closet, big enough to hold a laptop, was no extra charge. The bed was more comfortable than those in pricier SF hotels. We also had a flat-screen TV. The shower had great water pressure and no shortage of hot water. We stayed seven nights and could not have been more pleased with this hotel. The hotel has a great restaurant (the place was hopping on Saturday night), and there are many others nearby. The location was terrific for us. This hotel was the best bargain we've ever had in San Francisco.	
Mar 4 2008 	Not what I was expecting	I wasn't &quot;forced&quot; to book this hotel, but it was the location where the conference I had enrolled in was, so I went ahead and booked it without doing my usual &quot;due diligence&quot; in shopping for the &quot;right&quot; hotel. My plan was to book a nice room and have my family meet me at the end of the week, since it was advertised as close to &quot;Union Square&quot; in San Francisco. When the cab dropped me off out front, and as I was struggling with my suitcase, I was surprised to not even have anybody open the door for me - even though, it appeared someone from the hotel was standing out front. Nonetheless, I went ahead and made it in and checked in at the front desk.The person at the desk welcomed me and gave me some &quot;basic&quot; information about the hotel. He said that there was a nice breakfast in the morning's in the hotels attached restaurant for $7 per person. I was excited to hear this, as I was traveling on a limited per diem. First of all - don't let the websites pictures fool you about what the rooms look like. Yes - they are nice with hardwood floors, flat panel television, etc... unfortunately, however, the pictures must have been taken with a HUGE wide-angle lens. My &quot;Deluxe&quot; room that I paid extra for was extremely small! On the bright side, I was pleased to see that I had a coffee maker in the room.The first night sleep was very good - the bed was extremely comfortable. I was ready to start the day by brewing some coffee and head down for breakfast at the restaurant. When I showed up downstairs, there was a tray of danishes and croissants and some coffee. I asked about the breakfast and was told that the restaurant was having technical difficulties and would not open until the next day. Needless to say, the restaurant did not open once for breakfast for the rest of my stay.Another thing to be warned about - the homeless people in this neighborhood are abundant!!! I'm used to seeing 