Mar 14 2007	Hotel California -- what a lovely place	This was the perfect place for a two-night getaway with my husband. We come to San Francisco at least once a year, and while we are always looking for a bargain we really enjoy a place with good service and a little style, both of which this place had in spades. We arrived too early to check in, but the desk attendant graciously stored our bags and assured us that our room, 706, was &quot;very nice.&quot; She was right. The walls were a cheerful yellow, the bed was king-sized, the sheets were Egyptian cotton, there was a flat-screen TV and the floor was a highly polished wood. The windows actually open, which is a welcome change from the hermetically sealed towers one so often finds in corporate-run chains. We found the room on Travel Zoo and had never stayed there before, so all of this was a pleasant surprise. The hotel serves complementary wine and cheese from 4 - 6 p.m. -- nothing fancy but it was a welcome snack one afternoon when we arrived back after a long walk. A bowl of Granny Smith apples sits on the reception desk, there for the taking, and coffee and tea is available all day, also free of charge. The hotel is on the corner of Geary and Jones, on the Tenderloin side of Union Square. It's an easy walk to Union Square as well as to the Powell St . BART station. The Embarcadero is a pleasant 20-min walk away. We stayed over the weekend and this area is full of bars and therefore noisy at night. The double-paned windows help, as do earplugs. If you forget yours they have a good selection at the Walgreen's right down the block. If you are light-sensitive when you sleep bring something to cover your eyes. The window coverings here let in a fair amount of light, though this room faces west so at least there's no direct a.m. sun. I think we really lucked out with our room -- this is a small hotel and I noticed while we were riding the windowed elevator that some of the interior rooms face the elevator -- when the room shades were open you could see the beds from the elevator! It would have been a major bummer if we'd gotten one of these rooms. For us this was a great place to stay. Having stayed there only once I can't say if our visit was charmed or typical.	
Mar 3 2007 	Nice Hotel Great location	My wife and I spent one night at the Hotel California Feb 23rd on the second night of our most recent trip to California. The hotel was clean and comfortable and the staff from check-in until we checked out was superb. They couldn't do enough for us, giving us local maps and marking points of interest, offering ideas for evening drinks and dinner within a few blocks of the hotel and giving us two city passes left at the desk by previous guests. Our room was somewhat small but beautifully appointed. Nice comfortable bed, hard wood floors and nice bright colors and prints on the walls. The hotel has complimentary wine and cheese between 4-6 pm. Both were fine but nothing exceptional. Considering it was complimentary though it was a nice touch.Breakfast was included in our package and was served in the Millennium Restaurant on the first floor of the hotel. Eggs, breads, muffins and fantastic granola.The location of the hotel is superb. If ambitious you can walk a few blocks to Union Square, down through Chinatown and to Fisherman's Wharf and back. We walked back from the Wharf on Jones St. Great walk but quite a steep hill. The views of the bay are fantastic though so if you're up to it I suggest this walk.A few more recommendations. Walk to the Intercontinental Mark Hopkins Hotel a few blocks away on California St. and have a drink at their bar on the top floor of the hotel. Awesome views of the entire city. Have a drink before dinner at the Clift Hotel just down the street from the Hotel California. Great drinks and a good place to people watch.If you like Indian food, the New Delhi Restaurant a few blocks away on Ellis St. is wonderful. If you like it spicy try their Chicken Madras or Chicken Vindaloo. Both delicious.Overall, high marks for the Hotel California. We'd stay here again.	
Feb 12 2007	Pleasant reasonable and comfortable	We stayed here for a Friday and Saturday night, and there were many small things that added up to a very pleasant stay. Chad at the front desk was cheerful and helpful. We had a king deluxe room on the top floor, so it was relatively quiet, for being in the center of a big city. There is free internet access at two locations, in the lobby and mezzanine. The hot coffee in the lobby was fine, but you can use the small in-room coffemaker if you like. There is a complimentary wine, cheese and fruit buffet for two hours every day, and they offered us a tequila shot at check-in. Very hospitable! The beds were very comfortable, and I liked the upscale linens instead of those polyester bedspreads you still find in some places. The location, near many more expensive hotels, is convenient . I would stay here again.	
Feb 12 2007 	Noisy but charming	I stayed at this hotel in Feb 2006 when it was still called the Savoy Hotel. Some of the rooms on other levels were being renovated so there was some noise, but since we were out and about all day that didn't matter so much. What did matter and what was out of control of the hotel was all the noise on the streets. Mainly fire engines and yelling people. I don't know who was lighting all those fires but even earplugs couldn't block those sirens out. The people I think were drunk hobos and tourists and were yelling out random stuff all night long. Maybe the intensity of the noise was due to the location of our room, but it was really difficult to sleep.The room itself was ultra-tiny. But it was very nicely deocrated, had everything we wanted, including some complimentary chocolates and painting on the ceiling. I loved how they'd painted the lyrics to 'Hotel California' by the Eagles around the ceiling. Nice touch.The bathroom was a good size and everything worked satisfactorily. The bed was comfortable, and the tv reception was good.I love that they offered free internet access for guests though you had to pick a quiet time to use the computers.We didn't try out the restaurant on the ground floor but I wish we did, it looked very nice and the food smelled good too.The staff were helpful, a few gave us a tiny bit of attitude but overall they were great.The location was good, it's a few blocks walk to Union Square and the trams. There are bars, diners and cafes all around it. Be sure to avoid Dotties for breakfast. Everyone says it's good there but all i got was attitude and half-cooked blueberry pancakes. The coffee was crap too. There are plenty of other eateries to enjoy.I'd stay here again. I'd love to see what they've done with the place since my visit.	
